# 3-2-1 Backup & Recovery Homelab

A complete enterprise-style 3-2-1 backup strategy built on a home Ubuntu Server using a 5TB external HDD and LAN network shares. Every tool used is free and open source — total software cost is $0.

This lab is part of an ongoing homelab portfolio focused on hands-on SOC analyst / defensive security skills, documented for [CompTIA Security+ SY0-701](https://www.comptia.org/certifications/security) study and GitHub/LinkedIn visibility.

## Why this lab

Backup and recovery is a core Security+ Domain 4 (Security Operations) topic, and it's one of the few security controls every organization — from a homelab to an enterprise — actually has to operate, not just configure once. Most "backup" tutorials stop at `rsync -av source dest`. This lab goes further: encryption at rest, automated scheduling, retention policies, integrity verification, a tested restore, and SIEM alerting on failure — the full lifecycle a SOC analyst would actually be responsible for monitoring.

## Architecture

```
┌─────────────────────┐
│   Ubuntu Server       │  Source: /home/[user]
│   (homelab)           │
└──────────┬────────────┘
           │
           ├─────────────► Copy 2 (Local): 5TB USB HDD at /mnt/backup
           │                 ├── rsync incremental sync (daily, 2 AM)
           │                 └── Restic AES-256 encrypted snapshots (daily, 3 AM)
           │
           └─────────────► Copy 3 (Network): Samba SMB share
                             └── Accessible to other LAN devices for offsite-style copy

Wazuh SIEM agent monitors backup logs → custom rules alert on FAILURE events
```

**The 3-2-1 rule applied:**
- **3 copies:** original data + local HDD copy + network share copy
- **2 media types:** internal server disk + external USB HDD
- **1 offsite-equivalent:** Samba network share, reachable by any other device on the LAN

## Technologies used

| Tool | Purpose | Cost |
|---|---|---|
| rsync | Incremental delta backups, scheduled via cron | Free |
| cron | Linux task scheduler for automated daily backups | Free |
| Samba | SMB/CIFS network share for LAN-based backup access | Free |
| Restic | AES-256-CTR encrypted, deduplicated snapshot backups | Free |
| Wazuh SIEM | Custom rules monitoring backup success/failure events | Free (already deployed) |

